    "abstract": [],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "The COVID-19 outbreak in Wuhan city, China, in December 2019 has rapidly spread up to the level of Pandemia at the beginning of March 2020. A recent report from China has identified high inflammatory status as a predictor of adverse outcome, suggesting that mortality might be due to virally driven hyper-inflammation status [1] .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 325,
                    "end": 328,
                    "text": "[1]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "There is a well-established link between inflammation and increased risk of deep vein thrombosis (DVT). A potential explanation is that vessel wall inflammation initiates thrombus formation, through the activation of endothelial cells, platelets, and leukocytes that trigger the coagulation pathway [2, 3] .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 299,
                    "end": 302,
                    "text": "[2,",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 303,
                    "end": 305,
                    "text": "3]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "Additionally, procoagulant state has long been recognized also as part of ARDS pathophysiology, demonstrated by the identification of diffuse pulmonary endothelial injury associated with platelets' activation, macro-and micro-thrombi thought to be either embolic, formed in situ or both [4] . Moreover, the interaction pathway among platelets, neutrophils, and endothelial cells' dysfunction in ARDS has been associated with deep vein thrombosis development [2] . High prevalence of acute pulmonary embolism (APE) has been recently reported in patients admitted with COVID-19-related pneumonia [5] .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 287,
                    "end": 290,
                    "text": "[4]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                },
                {
                    "start": 458,
                    "end": 461,
                    "text": "[2]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 594,
                    "end": 597,
                    "text": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "We report the prevalence of venous thrombotic events in patients consecutively admitted to the ICU of a Hub Hospital for SARS-CoV-2 since the beginning of the Italian outbreak infection on February 21, 2020. Informed consent was collected following the ad hoc procedures defined by the Ethics Committee for the COVID-19 pandemic.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "All patients were sedated, mechanically ventilated and treated with prophylactic low-molecular-weight heparin (LMWH) adjusted on body weight since the admission.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "Eight out of 54 patients (14.8%) were diagnosed with deep vein thrombosis, 6 of which were central catheterrelated. Additionally, one patient had a thrombotic formation attached to the tricuspid valve in the absence of predisposing factors. Sub-segmental pulmonary embolism was found in two patients examined with computed tomography pulmonary angiography (CTPA) and one patient died of cardiac arrest with pulseless electrical activity (PEA) as presentation rhythm and sudden right ventricular dilatation.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "In our experience 22.2% of patients (83% male, 68 \u00b1 7 years old; BMI 29.3 \u00b1 4.4 kg/m 2 ; C-reactive protein 25.7 \u00b1 9.2 mg/dl, fibrinogen 657.1 \u00b1 200.6 mg/dl) admitted to ICU due to SARS-CoV-2 interstitial pneumonia had venous thrombotic events (Fig. 1) .",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 244,
                    "end": 252,
                    "text": "(Fig. 1)",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF0"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "ICU admission and ARDS are considered both predisposing factors for a number of reasons, including the need for prolonged immobilization and hyper-inflammatory state. The prevalence of vein thrombosis in patients admitted with ARDS is currently unknown.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "A recent report showed that 10 out of 25 patients admitted with pneumonia due to COVID-19 presented sub-segmental APE, assessed with CPTA. No associated deep vein thrombosis was reported as the authors did not perform ultrasound screening.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        },
        {
            "text": "Because of the pathophysiological link between inflammation and thrombosis development [3] , especially in critically ill patients, the hyper-inflammatory status of patients with COVID-19 [1] and the high prevalence of APE [5] and of vein thrombotic events found in our population, we strongly suggest that a close vein ultrasound screening and monitoring should be performed in all ",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 87,
                    "end": 90,
                    "text": "[3]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                },
                {
                    "start": 188,
                    "end": 191,
                    "text": "[1]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 223,
                    "end": 226,
                    "text": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor,"
        }
    ],
